          "content": {
            "size": 2375,
            "mimeType": "text/html",
            "compression": 0,
            "text": "<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN\" \"http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/loose.dtd\">\r\n<html>\r\n<head><link rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" media=\"all\" href=\"css/jScrollPane.css\">\r\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"css/help.css\">\r\n<link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"css/scrollbar.css\">\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"jquery.js\"></script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"script/jquery.mousewheel.js\"></script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"script/jScrollPane.js\"></script>\r\n\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"script/script.js\"></script>\r\n\r\n<META name=\"description\" content='C7000v2'>\r\n<META http-equiv=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=utf-8\">\r\n<META http-equiv=\"Content-Style-Type\" content=\"text/css\">\r\n<META http-equiv=\"Pragma\" content=\"no-cache\">\r\n<META HTTP-equiv=\"Cache-Control\" content=\"no-cache\">\r\n<META HTTP-EQUIV=\"Expires\" CONTENT=\"Mon, 06 Jan 1990 00:00:01 GMT\">\r\n\r\n<title>NETGEAR Gateway C7000v2</title>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">\r\n<!--\r\n $(document).ready(function() {\r\n        $('#content').jScrollPane('scrollbarMargin:5px');\r\n     parent.showHelpIframe();\r\n\t\t// Workaround for known Opera issue which breaks demo (see\r\n\t// http://jscrollpane.kelvinluck.com/known_issues.html#opera-scrollbar )\r\n\t\t// IE calculates the width incorrectly first time round (it\r\n\t\t// doesn't count the space used by the native scrollbar) so\r\n\t\t// we re-trigger if necessary.\r\n\t});\r\n//-->\r\n</script>\r\n\r\n</head>\r\n<body style='margin:0px'><div id='content' style='overflow:auto;scrolling:auto;width:100%;height:140px'><P><B style='font-size:14pt'>Connection Help</B></P><p>You can use the <I>Connection</I> page to track your gateway's initialization procedure, and to get details on the Downstream and Upstream cable channel.<ul> <li><B>Extended Upstream Transmit Power:</B> Click to enable the Extended Upstream Transmit Power. This allows the Cable device to transmit at a higher upstream power to overcome the attenuation in the upstream channels. In case your service provider set the Extended Upstream Transit Power on this Cable device permanently, this option is grayed out and cannot be changed.</ul><ul> <li><B>Current System Time:</B> After the cable modem is initialized you can see the current time.</ul><ul> <li><B>System Up Time:</B> This is the time on how long the device is up since last reboot.</ul></div></body>\r\n</html>\r\n\r\n"
          },
